Your problem is really just a matter of using the right query type. I assume you're using LINQ to SQL, so the correct query type is Entity Framework's query expression.
First, you need to define a class representing your data, and define a table for it:
public class Item
{
    public int Id;
    public string Title;
    public string Description;
}

public class MyDb : DbContext
{
    public DbSet<Item> Item { get; set; }
}

And then you can use it like this:
var result = from item in MyDb.Item
             where item.Title == "Test"
             select item;

result will create a query expression that matches the LINQ to SQL query, and will return an IEnumerable<Item> that contains all items that match the filter in the query expression.
If you're using LINQ to SQL in a non-LINQ context, you can create a similar query expression, but you need to use the object entity type instead of the standard types:
var result = from item in MyDb.Item.OfType<Item>
             where item.Title == "Test"
             select item;

result will create a query expression that matches the LINQ to SQL query, and will return an IEnumerable<object> that contains all items that match the filter in the query expression.

