A:

The first two are a simple matter of a loop and a condition.
while (something) {
  doSomething();
  if (somethingElse) return;
}

In the third case, you would wrap the logic in a function:
function doSomethingElse() {
  // do whatever you want here
}

function doSomething() {
  somethingElse = true;
  doSomethingElse();
  somethingElse = false;
}

The last example is a bit more involved, because you have to keep track of the state of somethingElse.
function thing() {
  if (somethingElse) {
    doSomethingElse();
  }
  else {
    return;
  }
}

You could also wrap the logic in a closure.
var thing = function() {
  if (somethingElse) {
    doSomethingElse();
  }
  else {
    return;
  }
};

So to answer your question about the three clauses:

the while loop is an example of a function call that goes out of its way to return something.
the if statement is an example of a function call that has no direct return value, but is designed to be called inside a loop.
the function with the closure is an example of a function that returns something in the context of a loop.

